# Performance and Core Web Vitals

Page experience is a confirmed ranking signal and a real user-experience floor. Target these field thresholds:
- **LCP < 2.5s** (loading)
- **INP < 200ms** (responsiveness, replaced FID in 2024 and is the most commonly failed metric)
- **CLS < 0.1** (visual stability)

## Images
- Always `next/image`. Set `width`/`height` (or `fill` with a sized container) so space is reserved and CLS stays low.
- Serve modern formats (AVIF/WebP). Add `priority` to the LCP image (usually the hero) and preload it. Lazy-load everything below the fold.
- Descriptive `alt` on every meaningful image (accessibility, image search, and CLS all benefit). Empty `alt=""` only for purely decorative images.

## Fonts
- Use `next/font` to self-host and preload fonts. This removes render-blocking font requests and font-swap layout shift. Never pull fonts from a third-party `<link>`.

## JavaScript and INP
- Minimise client JS. Keep components as Server Components unless they need interactivity; hydrate the smallest possible client leaves.
- Load third-party scripts (analytics, chat widgets, pixels) with `next/script` using `strategy="afterInteractive"` or `"lazyOnload"`. Third-party scripts are the top cause of INP failures, so gate non-essential ones behind consent and defer them.
- Avoid large client-side libraries where a server component or a small utility would do.

## Layout stability
- Reserve space for anything that loads late: images, embeds, ads, dynamic banners. Never inject content above existing content after load.
- Use `Suspense` boundaries and proper loading UI so streaming does not cause shifts.

## Before shipping
Assume every new page will be checked in PageSpeed Insights / Lighthouse against the three thresholds above. If a change is likely to regress LCP or INP (a heavy client component, an unoptimised hero image, a synchronous third-party script), call it out and offer the lighter alternative.
